I was able to reproduce a distinct jerkiness in a Java version of your animation.  At first I thought it was a result of repaint requests being coalesced, which is a known and intentional mechanism by which Swing can shed work when stressed. But that shouldn&#39;t happen if the event-dispatch thread is not stressed, and it clearly wasn&#39;t.

I eventually discovered that I could resolve the issue by invoking `getToolkit().sync()` to the end of `paintComponent()`.  This tells me that, at least in my case, the issue was not that the panel was not being repainted by Swing, but that multiple repaints were being performed between updates of the native peer.  And that also explains why I found that waving the mouse pointer over the window relieved the jerkiness: Swing knew it had to update the peer to paint the portion revealed by moving the mouse pointer.

In addition, I pushed all the GUI work into the EDT, where it needs to be, and made some other minor adjustments.  This is my final result (in Java, not the equivalent Kotlin):
```
import java.awt.*;
import java.time.*;
import java.util.Optional;
import javax.swing.*;
import static java.lang.Math.cos;
import static java.lang.Math.PI;
import static java.lang.Math.sin;

public class GraphicsDemo {

    final static int TICK_DELAY = 10;

    static class DemoPanel extends JPanel {

        private Optional&lt;Instant&gt; startInstant = Optional.empty();

        public DemoPanel() {
            super(true);
            setPreferredSize(new Dimension(1200, 800));
            setBackground(Color.BLUE);
        }

        void updateState() {
            // ...
            repaint();
        }

        @Override
        protected void paintComponent(Graphics g) {
            super.paintComponent(g);
            Instant now = Instant.now();

            if (!startInstant.isPresent()) {
                startInstant = Optional.of(now);
            }
            double centisElapsed
                    = Duration.between(startInstant.get(), now).toMillis() / 10.0;

            int x = 1200 + (int) (centisElapsed * sin(centisElapsed * PI / 720) / 5);
            int y =  800 + (int) (centisElapsed * cos(centisElapsed * PI / 720) / 5);

            // Copy the Graphics object because we&#39;re going to persistently modify it
            Graphics2D g2D = (Graphics2D) g.create();

            g2D.scale(0.5, 0.5);
            g2D.setColor(Color.BLACK);
            g2D.fillRect(x, y, 200, 200);
            g2D.dispose();

            // This was important:
            getToolkit().sync();
        }
    }

    // This method should be run on the EDT
    public static void startGUI() {
        JFrame mainWindow = new JFrame(&quot;GraphicsDemo&quot;);

        DemoPanel panel = new DemoPanel();
        // javax.swing.Timer: fires events on the EDT
        Timer animationTimer = new Timer(TICK_DELAY, ae -&gt; panel.updateState());

        mainWindow.setDefaultCloseOperation(WindowConstants.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        mainWindow.setResizable(false);
        mainWindow.add(panel);
        mainWindow.pack();

        mainWindow.setVisible(true);
        animationTimer.start();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        EventQueue.invokeAndWait(GraphicsDemo::startGUI);
    }
}
```

